    "y": "35.59",
    "x": "50.021999",
    "style": {},
    "fill": "#007bff"
  }))))), mdx("p", null, "The most important aspect to ensuring that your customers (whether they be internal or external to the walls of your company) are considered is simply by communicating. Involving them in the project will allow them to feel as though they\u2019re part of the end solution, emotionally investing them in the success of it. The other major benefit of doing this is leveraging them for their ideas. A common failure that I see in DS teams is that they believe that they can tackle problems through only using data. I\u2019ve never found that to be a particularly successful pattern of behavior, noticing instead that many weeks of effort can be saved by a short 30 minute conversation with the people who truly understand the problem. "), mdx("p", null, "This becomes a bit harder to do for external customers (obviously), but even in the business to consumer model of business there exists the ability to gain feedback through the use of focus groups. Never underestimate the sheer amount of frustrating rework that you can avoid with just a simple friendly chat with people who understand the nuances behind the collected data and those who are consuming the predictions."), mdx("h3", {
